<i>HS: Hi Alexis, I  typically tear rustic day old bread into bite-sized pieces, toss it with a few glugs of olive oil, then spread out on a baking sheet in a single layer. Bake at 350 until well toasted. I usually have some sort of whole grain bread around, but like making these with olive or walnut bread as well.</i></p></p></div></div><div class="commentdivide">&nbsp;</div><br class="clear" /><div id="c-234413" class="singlecomment"><div class="commenthead"><a title="http://www.theironyou.com" href="http://www.theironyou.com" rel="nofollow">Mike @TheIronYou</a> <div class="commentdate">April  6, 2012</div></div><div class="commentbox"><p>Haven't seen broccolini yet at the farmer's market this year...but I'm definitely on the hunt. This recipe looks amazing!</p></div></div><div class="commentdivide">&nbsp;</div><br class="clear" /><div id="c-234415" class="singlecomment"><div class="commenthead"><a title="http://madscientistskitchen.blogspot.in/" href="http://madscientistskitchen.blogspot.in/" rel="nofollow">Archana</a> <div class="commentdate">April  6, 2012</div></div><div class="commentbox"><p>Wow I am sure this  tasted awesome. </p></div></div><div class="commentdivide">&nbsp;</div><br class="clear" /><div id="c-234417" class="singlecomment"><div class="commenthead"><a title="http://foodwinemine.com" href="http://foodwinemine.com" rel="nofollow">Meg</a> <div class="commentdate">April  6, 2012</div></div><div class="commentbox"><p>That looks so good! Perfect for easter! </p></div></div><div class="commentdivide">&nbsp;</div><br class="clear" /><div id="c-234418" class="singlecomment"><div class="commenthead"><a title="http://www.zomppa.com" href="http://www.zomppa.com" rel="nofollow">Belinda @zomppa</a> <div class="commentdate">April  6, 2012</div></div><div class="commentbox"><p>What a beautiful salad!! Stunner!</p></div></div><div class="commentdivide">&nbsp;</div><br class="clear" /><div id="c-234419" class="singlecomment"><div class="commenthead"><a title="